<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-660-253  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 660 253.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Oct 1990 v27 n10 p66(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer-aided Randamp;D: chips are at the cutting edge. (Randamp;D SpecialIssue Part 3 ...so what's to be done?)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Murphy, Erin E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-aided design and computer-aided engineering (CAD-CAE)tools are used more often by corporations that want to speedproduct life cycles.andP;  CAD-CAE was first used extensively by thesemiconductor industry.andP;  Design tools became necessary as devicecomplexity grew; the design of a one-million-device processor, forinstance, necessitates use of modern CAE tools.andP;  CAD tools areused to automate routine tasks and to simulate ICs at a highlevel.andP;  In a few years it is expected that designers will havetools to help them mix analog and digital logic on the same chip.andO;Future testing strategies may be dominated by design fortestability.andP;  Built-in self test is another strategy that designtools may eventually support.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignComputer-Aided EngineeringCircuit DesignValidationSimulation TheoryResearch and DevelopmentFuture of Computing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>